@Charlene yes, that  happened to me today. 
I added more butter to equal 1 1/4 c but I just baked them and they didn’t spread at all. I ended up dropping he baking sheet which spread them out a bit. 
Also, I made the toffee using a candy thermometer and the toffee was burnt tasting, so I ended up buying some to make the cookies. They are delicious but I need to make some tweaks. I wonder if the flour I used (King Arthur all purpose with 11.7% protein) is the issue, since I weighed my ingredients. Did anyone else have drier dough and no spread?

@Mary Carol Blauser
I 100% agree with you.  I only bake with nut flour and have delicious recipes I've used for years. 
 It’s a special treat to see a New York Times recipe that only uses nut flour.

First time I made this recipe I had these happy accidents, which I now deliberately incorporate every time:

1): Let the butter brown, it adds an amazing nutty undertone;
2): Leave any unmelted lumps alone!  They contribute texture, and provide surprising  chocolatey bites;
3): Make bigger cookies.  I eyeballed the size, got 10 instead of 18, and baked for the exact same time.  Result: ooey, gooey yuminess that stayed pliable even directly from the freezer.
